                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">Earning your bachelor’s degree in Communication Disorders is a common pathway for advanced graduate study in audiology or speech language pathology. Speech-language pathologists diagnose and treat individuals with articulation, language, voice, fluency, cognitive communication, social communication and swallowing disorders.  </p>
                                  <p class="mb-4 size-18">If you want to become an speech language pathologist (SLP), our bachelor’s program in Communication Disorders will help you build a strong foundation. As an SLP, you will work with clients of all ages including those with Parkinson’s, autism spectrum disorders, strokes, brain injuries, Down syndrome, apraxia of speech and hearing impairments.  </p>
                                  <h4 class="header-colorize">Why Study Communication Disorders at Marshall?</h4>
